The USA Gymnastics supports the letter of the United States Olympic Committee and recognizes the absolute necessity from the Olympic community to work to create a safe environment for all its athletes.
We agree with what was said by the USOC, namely that the interests of our athletes and our clubs, and of their sport, can be better served by bringing about a significant change within our organization, and not with decertification.
The USA Gymnastics has promoted an independent investigation to understand how it was possible that an abuse of the dimensions described with such courage by those who have been able to survive Larry Nassar remained hidden for so long, and is willing to implement any necessary or appropriate change.
USA Gymnastics and USOC have the same goal: to make gymnastics and other sports as safe as possible, so that athletes can pursue their dreams in an environment that is reliable, positive and responsible.
In the 1960s, Brzezinski was an advisor to John F. Kennedy and later to Lyndon B. Johnson's administration.
In the course of the 1976 elections, he advised Carter on foreign policy and then served as National Security Advisor (NSA) from 1977 to 1981, succeeding Henry Kissinger.
As a member of the NSA, he collaborated with Carter in the diplomatic management of international affairs, including the Camp David Accords of 1978, the normalization of relations between China and the United States at the end of the 1970s, the Iranian Revolution (which led to the hostage crisis in Iran in 1979) and the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan in 1979.
